		<table width="90%" bgcolor="" style="border-collapse: collapse; border-left-width:1; border-right-width: 1; border-top-style: solid; border-left-style: solid; border-right-style: solid; border-bottom-style: solid; border-top-width: 1; border-bottom-width: 1" bordercolor="#FFFFFF" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" ID="Table2">  
		<tr>
			<td align="left" valign="top" background="/images/necrotableheader2.gif">
				<font width="100%" face="verdana" size="1" color=white><b>Agro kiting made easy</b>
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr bgcolor="#ffebdc">
			<td align="left" valign="top" valign="top">
				<font face="verdana" size="1" color=white>
				written by <b>umbrae</b> on <b>3/12/2003 8:35:46 AM</b>
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr bgcolor="#37437B">
			<td align="left" valign="top" valign="top">
				<font face="verdana" size="1" color=white><blockquote><br>
				First, Agro kiting is basically, making a mob mad at you, and running away, while your dots and or pet kill it.  A relatively simple tactic for killing things, often used by druids and bards, as well as necromancers.  I write this guide from a 65 necro with 30+ AA point of view, but it can easly be adapted for use at just about any level.<br><br>First thing, agro kiting is made allot easier if you can snare the mob you are trying to kill, although a kill can still be had on a snare immune mob.  Also, non summoning mobs make for better agro kiting, although once again, this is not required.  Note, high DPS summoning mobs will kill you, so agro kiting summoners in planes of power is akin to suicide.<br><br>Find an area you like with a bit of room to move around with agro, and a few close by mobs. Summon a pet, turn off pet taunt (if you use suspended minion to save on pet buffs, or pull, make sure you turn of pet taunt each time you resummon him, as it defaults to on), fully buff yourself and pet (buy virtue, protection of 9, or what ever buffs you like before hand).  I use Shield of Maelin, Force Shield, Rune of Death, Saryrn's Companion, and Spirit of Wolf (potions), but these can be substituted for similar lower level spells, I first stated hunting plane of valor agro kiting at 60, with the 56 pet, and only dark plague as a 61+ spell.  Split a single mob off through you preferred splitting method (guides writing assuming the mob is a solo pull, modify as needed for a split mob, but remember, snare adds a lot of agro, if your mob is already snared, and you FD split it, you drop agro, so you might want to resnare just for agro.<br><br>10 Does Blood of the Wolf potions, and Spell haste rings from a mage are something you should always try to get if you are trying this for the first time.  I recommend getting them if you are going to agro kite at all.  Affliction haste can  substitute a general spell haste item, but speeding up you casting and movement are amazingly helpful for this.<br><br>Always when agro kiting, beware of mob pathing.  I have seen mobs turn around, run away from you, gain adds and come back, also there are some spots where mobs can warp right on top of you, although there is no obstacle in their way.  Pathing can also work to your advantage, although exploits will get you banned, if a mob takes a few extra steps to get to you, you can use that time to cast an extra spell, or maneuver around him.<br><br>Snareable, non summoning mobs:<br>My standard spell line up for these is as follows.  Saryrn's Kiss, Dooming Darkness (Embracing Darkness if I had it), Funeral Pyre of Kelador, Dark Plague, Pyrocruor, Cessation of Cor, Seduction of Saryrn (swapped for Rune of Death), Death Peace. I would replace Splurt with Cessation of Cor, unless you have that as a right clicker. Also, if you do not have Funeral Pyre of Kelador, you might want to use Cessation of Corin its place for the added agro.<br>Snare mob, get a bit of a lead on the mob, cast your highest DPS dot, get a bit of lead on the mob, cast your best agro dot, send in pet, get a bit of a lead on your target, reapply dots as necessary, making sure to avoid mob melee while doing so.  You will probably end up running in a small figure 8.  making your mob walk down a path, with a small circle at the end to turn the mob around on the path without getting hit.<br>Make sure to reapply dark early, this helps add a bit of agro, as well as giving you some room should you get a resist.  On highly magic resistant mobs, you might want to resnare 30+ seconds before snare is due to wear off.<br>Learning the timing of casting a spell is something that can only be gained with experience in agro kiting.  But basic rule of thumb, if you think the mob is going to hit you once or twice, just run, recast when you have a better lead on the mob.  I do not know how many times I have been stunned, interrupted and quickly killed because I did not do just that.<br><br>Snare immune, non summoning mobs:<br>These are a bit harder to take down that snareable mobs, and at least SoW speed or grater is a must.  Buy SoW potions of need be, or get a fast horse if you can.  Make sure you are fully buffed before hand, as there will be no swapping of spells.<br>You will have much less time to cast spells against snare immune mobs, so plan accordingly.  My standard spell line up is<br>Touch of Mujaki, Funeral Pyre of Kelador, Clinging Darkness, Siphon Strength, Shadow Vortex, Disease Cloud, Seduction of Saryn, and Death Peace.  If you do not have Funeral Pyre of Kelador, use what ever spell you prefer for agro, Cession of Cor is a good choice.<br>You will need a some what larger area to kite these, as it is harder to get a lead and cast.  The spells I have listed are all quick casting spells, usually with low damage, but several have good agro potential.  Clinging Darkness, Siphon Strength, Shadow Vortex all have low cast times and high agro.  Although they do no damage, this should allow you to maintain agro over your pet which will be doing 99% of the damage this fight.  Also, you pet will not be constantly hitting as most mobs can outrun you pet.  If you can get a sow for you pet do so, but beware, a constantly hitting pet can some times pull agro off you, so you might want to back your pet off from time to time, or use pet fein death if you have it.<br>First, cast Funeral Pyre of Kelador.  Unless you have affliction haste (don’t think mage summoned spell hast will work) this will be the only cast of pyre you get off.<br>Now RUN!!!!! Run until you are out of casting range if you can, then cast Clinging Darkness, Siphon Strength, or Shadow Vortex.  My personal preference is Shadow Vortex.  You should not have enough agro to send in your pet.  Each time you get enough of a lead cast something.  If you get hit, or when Litch pulls you down enough, once again get out of cast range and start hammering the touch of mujaki spell.  It should land just before the mob hits you.<br><br>Snareable, Summoning Mobs:<br>This does depend a bit from mob to mob, but most mobs do not summon all that quickly.<br>Spell line up<br>Saryns kiss, Touch of Mujaki, Dooming Darkness (Embracing Darkness if I had it), Funeral Pyre of Kelador, Dark Plague, Force Shield, Seduction of Saryrn (swapped for Rune of Death), Death Peace.<br>Most mobs require that you do X amount of damage to them before they start to summon you.  This means you can probably lay down 1 round of dots before getting summoned.  Once you start getting summoned there are two basic strategies.<br>One is to recast force shield over and over, their by taking little to no damage as the mob is just trying to eat though your shield (if you do not have force shield I would not recommend this, not only does Manaskin absorb less HP but it take a peridot, and will cost you a lot of plat per kill).  The other is to use Touch of Mujaki / Saryrn's Kiss to compensate for damage being taken.  It really depends on how quickly to mob summons VS their DPS as to which you should use, but basically the work the same.<br>Snare your mob, run a bit, and get some dots on it. Wait for it to summon you, as soon as it does, run away, and either recast a dot, snare, life tap, or force shield before it summons you again.<br>This takes a good amount of practice to get this down, for if you run to far, you will get summoned while casting and interrupted,  if you do not run far enough you will get hit a few extra times.  Both of these could mean the death of you.<br>If you get summoned, run.  Let the spell finish, it is interrupted if you get summoned, so just run ASAP to avoid melee.<br><br>Snare Immune, Summoning mobs<br>Spell Line up: Gate, Quivering Veil of Xarn, Harm Shield, Death Peace.<br>Run to the zone, Gate, FD and /q out, but Get the hell out of their before you die!<br>If it is undead you might be able to slow it and tank it with Touch of Mujaki, but that would not be agro kiting now would it ;)<br><br>&nbsp;<br>
			</td>
		</tr>
